AB A study of caregiving issues for 51 caregivers of stroke patients in Taiwan investigated the relationship among caregiving burden, functional status, cognitive level of patients, perceived social supports and attitudes toward providing long-term care, gender and type of caregiver, and selected demographic variables. No significant correlations were found between the caregiver burden, functional status, or cognitive level of the patient, although results were in the desired direction. Significant differences were found between spousal and adult child caregivers, between female and male caregivers, and between some pairs of variables. Findings that suggest further research about the dynamics of the Taiwanese family caregiving network are needed.
